    "summary": "Sierra Leone's civil war (1991–2002) was notable for its extraordinary brutality and the systematic use of atrocity as a deliberate military and political strategy. The Revolutionary United Front (RUF), initially backed by Liberian warlord Charles Taylor, began an insurgency from the east of the country in 1991. The RUF became notorious for amputating the limbs of civilians — including children — burning villages, and abducting thousands of children as soldiers. The conflict killed tens of thousands and displaced half of the country's population.\n\nThe war was intimately connected to the exploitation of Sierra Leone's diamond fields, which financed rebel operations in what became a widely discussed example of the so-called resource curse. International attention and outrage grew through the 1990s, and British military intervention in 2000 helped stabilize the situation and rescue a besieged UN peacekeeping force. Peace was formally restored in 2002. A Special Court for Sierra Leone subsequently tried and convicted senior RUF commanders and, in a historic precedent, Charles Taylor of Liberia — the first sitting head of state convicted of war crimes since Nuremberg.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sierra_Leone_Civil_War",
